2024 Election Review: The Rise of Crypto in Politics, Initial Market Reactions, and the Success of Prediction Markets

Dylan Bane
Andrew Dyer

Nov 8, 2024 ⋅  12 min read

Donald Trump will be the 47th President of the United States.

While the media will analyze every aspect of Tuesday’s result and the coming Trump Presidency, Messari is focused on the election’s impact on crypto markets and the industry more broadly.

Crypto’s Role in the 2024 Election

Crypto became a salient policy issue late in the election cycle. Industry advocacy groups spent much of the prior two years quietly building influence in Washington and raising funds for pro-crypto interests in the 2024 elections. Around half of campaign donations this cycle are estimated to have come from crypto-focused groups.

The watershed moment for crypto policy occured at an NFT event hosted by Trump at Mar-a-Lago on May 8th, 2024. At this event, Trump stated, "If crypto is moving out of the U.S. because of hostility toward crypto... well, we’ll stop it. We don’t want that,” inviting crypto industry leaders on stage, including Polygon Founder Mihailo Bjelic and Messari founder Ryan Selkis.

From there, Trump quickly adopted a favorable stance toward the industry, meeting with industry leaders and promoting crypto. By late July, Trump took the main stage at Bitcoin Nashville, making the following promises at the conference and over the course of his campaign:

  • Fire SEC Commissioner Gary Gensler.
  • Introduce a national strategic Bitcoin reserve.
  • Pardon Silk Road Founder Ross Ulbricht.
  • Appoint a Bitcoin and crypto presidential council to design regulatory reforms.
  • Ensure that Bitcoin continues to be mined in the U.S.
  • Make the U.S. the “Crypto Capital” of the world.
  • Remove capital gains taxes on Bitcoin transactions.
  • Ensure that the U.S. does not introduce a CBDC.

Going into August, much of the crypto industry rallied behind Trump as their best hope to fight increasing scrutiny from the SEC’s regulation-by-enforcement approach. Crypto advocacy groups claimed that the over 50 million Americans who own crypto would be pivotal in determining the election outcome.

In response, the newly formed Harris campaign in August displayed openness to working with the crypto industry to enact potential favorable regulation for the crypto industry. However, promises were vague, limiting the appeal of a Harris Presidency to much of the crypto industry.

By election day, Trump had chosen a pro-crypto VP in Vance, launched a crypto protocol in World Liberty Financial, conducted a Bitcoin transaction at the only Bitcoin Bar in the US, and proposed to pay off the national debt with “$35 trillion in crypto”. While many claims seemed unrealistic in Trump’s characteristic egregious rhetoric, he appeared to be the candidate best representing crypto’s interests in the eyes of many industry participants.

When Trump decisively won the election on November 5th, much of the industry celebrated a potential golden era for crypto with deregulation in the U.S. and a pro-crypto administration.

Since the election on November 5th, crypto markets reacted positively, rising nearly 11% over the last week. Furthermore, one of the emerging successful use cases for the industry, prediction markets, even called the election hours before mainstream media.

Messari analysts seek to answer how markets have reacted to the 2nd Trump Presidency and what the election results mean more broadly for the crypto industry.

The Rise of Prediction Markets

One of the most prominent stories of election day was the relative accuracy of prediction markets compared to traditional media and polling. Polymarket, a prediction market on Polygon, estimated a 61.7% chance of winning for Trump compared to 38.4% for Harris going into election day. At the same time, traditional polls had both candidates at a virtual 50-50 tie.

By 11:43 PM on election night, Polymarket assigned an over 95% chance of Trump winning the election, effectively calling the race nearly 3 hours earlier than Fox News and 6 hours earlier than the Associated Press. As a result, market-driven prediction markets will likely receive increasing credibility as a source of public sentiment in elections going forward.

While Polymarket has outdone itself in displaying both the potential and the usefulness of a crypto app with product-market fit, it remains to be seen whether the platform can sustain high volumes outside of election cycles. Volumes and active trader levels unsurprisingly crashed on November 7th, but the election helped attract users to bet on other markets; non-election users increased from the beginning of October. It’s likely that sports markets - like the Champions League Winner - will dominate volumes going forward.

For more information on Polymarket and prediction markets, please see YES or NO on Polymarket and A New $Meta for DAOs.

Impact On Markets

Legacy Market Reaction

Trump’s victory sent traditional markets to all-time highs, with the S&P and Nasdaq both up more than ~2.5% on Wednesday. Both equity and bond volatility indices were crushed by 10-20% as election hedges were unwound. In addition, the dollar was up significantly as yields rose. The market appears to broadly expect that Trump's policies will spur higher growth and inflation. The stronger dollar was noticeably negative for gold, potentially bringing its multi-month, parabolic rally to an end as it finished down 3% on the day.

Crypto proxy stocks performed better than most of the technology sector. Robinhood and Coinbase were up more than 20-30%, benefitting from both an increase in expected trading volumes and an expected more friendly future regulatory environment. Microstrategy grew at a relatively lower 13% gain, however, it significantly outperformed Bitcoin before this post-election move. BTC miners like WULF, CLSK, MARA, and RIOT also grew by around 20% on the day.

Following Bitcoin's all-time highs Tuesday night, IBIT hit its typical daily trading volume for the day (around ~$1 billion) within the first 30 minutes of trading. Trading volumes reached a record $4.1 billion by the end of the day, while other ETFs traded around 2x their normal volumes. Furthermore, flows into all BTC ETFs reached over $600 million on Wednesday and more than $1.3 billion on Thursday. Even ETH, whose ETFs have largely been neglected (or used to rotate away from higher-fee ETHE) since launch, attracted around $50 million and ~$80 million in inflows on Wednesday and Thursday respectively.

Majors and a Shifting Tide

Majors rallied overnight and into the Wednesday close alongside legacy markets. With Elon Musk set to spearhead a Department of Government Efficiency (D.O.G.E), it’s no surprise the market picked both the longstanding DOGE and the new meme coin D.O.G.E. (on Ethereum) to express its bullishness. Two full days after the election, ETH is also starting to show more relative strength following an underwhelming 2024 so far.

Looking at the market capitalization of all tokens outside the top 10 (OTHERS index), we see that the average token has done a poor job keeping up with BTC since it topped in March. While there have been pockets of outperformance, we have not seen broad altcoin outperformance like in the past. ETH, as a bellwether of the average altcoin, may be signaling a catch-up is brewing, given its recent relative strength. Prior periods of ETH/BTC outperformance have been correlated with broader strength in the rest of the market.

A DeFi Revival - All Eyes on the Fee Switch

The market wasted little time in pricing in a friendlier regulatory environment under Trump and future Vice President J.D. Vance. Senator Vance in particular, has been known for scrutinizing the current SEC’s method of “regulation through enforcement.” The SEC notably moved against crypto giants like Uniswap and Consensys this year, spreading regulatory uncertainty throughout the industry and pushing innovation abroad. Furthermore, several Republican Senators, including Vance, wrote a scathing letter to the SEC earlier in the year about its regulatory approach. These negative remarks occurred after a judge overturned a ruling against DEBT Box, finding that the SEC made “materially false and misleading representations.” Vance and others rebuked the agency, stating:

“It is unconscionable that any federal agency—especially one regularly involved in highly consequential legal procedures and one that, under your leadership, has often pursued its regulatory mission through enforcement actions rather than rulemakings—could operate in such an unethical and unprofessional manner…That the Commission counsel could be so unfamiliar with the relevant facts of the case, and that Commission attorneys could have such little regard for the veracity of evidence presented to the Court is deeply troubling.”

It is likely that crypto developers and builders will have less to fear with a new SEC head who is more focused on the innovative potential of the underlying technology rather than enforcing 80-year-old securities laws.

Demonstrating the increased confidence in the industry, less than a full day after the election, Wintermute proposed turning on the fee switch for Ethena that would entitle ENA holders to a portion of protocol revenue. Wintermute notes that while direct allocations may be suboptimal given how new the protocol is, the possibility of directing revenue should be enabled to bring clarity to holders and the market. Turning on fee switches has been proposed for older protocols like Uniswap and Lido but has never been enacted - likely out of fear of regulatory crackdown and lawsuits. With a regime change, DeFi and other tokens that could direct real value to holders, enabling the protocols to be valued as businesses with real cash flows. While current valuations may be divorced from revenue based fundamentals, a friendly regulatory environment allows teams to innovate and ship more features they otherwise would not have. At the very least DeFi protocols face much less risk that before.

Other Sectors and Market Positioning

Outside of DeFi, traders and investors bought memes on the back of DOGE’s strength. As Messari analyst Sunny Shi pointed out, DOGE’s sizable market capitalization allows for favorable “valuation” comparisons versus smaller-cap memes; continued DOGE strength will likely trickle down to small and mid-cap memes.

We also saw strength in tokens already performing well before the election. Investors merely needed the uncertainty around the event to pass to allocate more heavily to prior winners. These include tokens like GOAT, GRASS, SUI, RAY, and others.

The broader market liquidated hundreds of millions of short positions on election night. Tokens that may have been popular short legs like EIGEN, SCR, ALEO, TIA, and others also had vicious squeezes as shorts unwound their hedges and directional bets.

One sector that received limited attention and flows was metaverse and gaming. Across the 80 largest gaming tokens that Messari tracks, the average token was only up around 2% in the past 24 hours (as of November 7) and around 5% in the last seven days. Based on data from the past two nights, tokens that never traded at least 10% higher would be considered significantly less performant than the broader market.

Ripple Effects Going Forward

Markets tend to struggle with pricing in significant regime shifts like the one we just had. Thinking through possible second and third-order effects is valuable in times like these. Some potential scenarios to consider:

  • BTC all-time highs attracted significant retail flow into the ETFs when they first launched. We’re already seeing that effect play out again in both flows and Coinbase app rankings (from 428 to 114 in the past few days). With renewed retail and institutional interest, new market participants may look to the ETH ETFs as a catch-up play as they seek exposure to the space.
  • A friendly regulatory environment likely means more potential IPOs by mature crypto companies like Circle. Visible exit paths for venture funding may attract more investors and lead to higher valuations in private markets, which should theoretically trickle down to public markets.
  • More tokens, more experiments, more building, and more innovation. Protocols and teams that could never consider launching a token–certain L2s and wallet creators (e.g. Metamask) in particular–are probably doing a deep dive right now on what that would look like. We should get a proliferation of experiments with new products and value accrual designs.
  • Head of Legal at Robinhood, Dan Gallagher, is rumored to be a potential front-runner for the new head of the SEC. Exchanges are going to have a lot more leeway with the products they introduce to users under this outcome.
  • US exchanges will also likely become more flexible with listings, potentially leading to large rallies for popular tokens that are either solely on-chain or on Asian exchanges only. It’s possible we see firms like Binance, hobbled in the US over the past four years, re-enter the US market.
  • Higher prices and more listings will most likely attract more trading activity and volumes. While CEXs like Coinbase will benefit, a portion of that new activity should shift to decentralized exchanges as DEX's share of volumes continues to grow. Hyperliquid and Raydium could be great picks-and-shovels plays in that regard.
  • Super-charged stablecoins – We’ll likely get much more regulatory clarity on stablecoins and see more rapid integrations into current payment rails after legislation is passed. More fintech companies will likely issue their own stablecoins, similar to how Robinhood and other platforms did last week.

While the election results bring much uncertainty for both the U.S. and the world, crypto markets appear to be reacting favorably to Trump’s victory. Messari will closely monitor policy and market developments to determine if the Trump Presidency makes good on campaign promises.
